Micro Focus Operations Orchestration (OO) uses business intelligence available in a content pack to automate certain IT processes. OO content packs are developed using the OO Studio application or the OO Web Designer application. Both OO Studio and OO Web Designer allows a developer to test and debug content pack locally and remotely on OO Central Server.&nbsp; Developers prefer to debug their OO content pack flows on a remote OO Central Server for the following reasons:<div><div><ol><li>Run time environment of OO Studio and OO Web Designer is different from OO Central Server.</li><li>Isolate and troubleshoot content pack flow issues on a live production OO Central Server.</li><li>Debug flow changes without making actual flow library changes on OO Central Server. Once results are satisfactory, content pack changes can be pushed to OO Central Server.</li></ol></div></div><div>When a remote debugger is run for an OO flow in an OO Studio that OO flow is run on a remote OO Central Server. Flows that are run remotely have a prefix of “Debug” in the “Run Name” of their flow execution. The following is a sample screenshot from OO Central UI showing two “SSH” OO flows that were run from a remote debugger. These two SSH OO flows have a prefix of “Debug” in their run name. The “Generate Random Number” flow runs were not debug runs as they do not have the prefix of “Debug” in their flow run name.<br></div><div><br></div><div><img src="./mediawiki/images/PN/OO-PurgeDebugEvents-RunExplorer.png"><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><span style="background-color: transparent;">Debugger flow execution is run with extended data persistence level and collects more data than a regular flow run.&nbsp; When a flow is debugged, debugger creates and stores following types of data in the database:</span><br></div><div><span style="background-color: transparent;"><div><br></div><div><ol><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Flow run execution data<br></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Debugger events data<br></span></li></ol><div><span style="background-color: transparent;">Flow run execution data is visible through the OO Central UI “run explorer” window. Debugger events data is stored in database tables such as “oo_debugger_events”. The debugger events data is not visible in OO Central UI. The following screenshot shows sample contents of “oo_debugger_events” table in the database.</span><br></div></div><div><span style="background-color: transparent;"><br></span></div><div><img src="./mediawiki/images/PN/OO-PurgeDebugEvents-QueryWindow.png"><span style="background-color: transparent;"><br></span></div><div><br></div><div>Every debugger flow execution contributes to increase in database size as it stores data in the database. It is highly recommended to purge both debugger flow execution data and debugger events data periodically to maintain optimal performance of Operations Orchestration. Use the following ways to purge debugger flow execution data and debugger events data on a recurring basis:<br></div><div><br></div><div><ol><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Micro Focus supplied database maintenance scripts.<br></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><div><div>Micro Focus supplied purging flows which are available in the solutions content pack.</div></div></span></li></ol><div><span style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:107%;
font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-fareast-font-family:
Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;
mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">This
article shows a power shell script that can be used to purge debugger events
data on-demand. Here are some of the script use cases and caveats:&nbsp;</span><br></div></div><div><span style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:107%;
font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-fareast-font-family:
Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;
mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA"><span style="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 107%;"><br></span></span></div><div><span style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:107%;
font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-fareast-font-family:
Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;
mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA"><span style="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 107%;">Script
use cases:</span><br></span></div><div><ul><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Use this script to purge debugger events data as required.</span></li></ul><div>Script caveats:<br></div></div><div><br></div><div><div><ul><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Use caution when running this script. This script purges debugger events data and cannot be recovered unless you have a database backup.<br></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">This script does not purge debugger flow run execution data. It purges debugger events data only. The debug flow run execution data continue to be visible in OO Central UI unless they are purged separately.<br></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Do not use this script to perform mass purge of debugger events data.<br></span></li><li><div>Do not schedule this script to purge debugger events data on a recurring basis. Instead, use Micro Focus supported database maintenance purge scripts and purging flows in the solution content pack. This script is not meant to replace Micro Focus supported database maintenance purge scripts and purging flows in the solutions content pack.<br></div></li></ul></div><div><span style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:107%;
font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-fareast-font-family:
Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;
mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">This
script can be further enhanced to meet your coding style, perform additional
checks required for your environment, to improve performance, to use as a
reference to develop it in your preferred programming language, to use as a
reference to make other OO REST API calls, etc. At a high level, this script
performs the following:</span><br></div><div><ul><li><span style="background-color: transparent;">Validates input values.&nbsp;<br></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><div><div><div>Purges debugger flow execution data based on the filters supplied via command line parameters.</div></div></div></span></li></ul></div></div><div><span style="background-color: transparent;">To run this script, follow the steps below:</span><br></div><div><span style="background-color: transparent;"><div><ol><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><span style="background-color: transparent;">Log on to a system running windows operating system.<br></span></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><span style="background-color: transparent;">Open a text editor.&nbsp;<br></span></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><span style="background-color: transparent;">Copy contents of this script to the text editor. Save the file as “OOPurgeDebugEvents.ps1”.<br></span></span></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><span style="background-color: transparent;">Open windows power shell. Navigate to the directory containing this power shell script.</span></span></li><li>Run the “OOPurgeDebugEvents.ps1” powershell script as follows: .\OOPurgeDebugEvents.ps1 -OOCentralURL&nbsp;<div>https://&lt;OOCentralHostName&gt;:&lt;Port&gt;/oo -UserName admin -Passwd &lt;AdminPassword&gt; -BeforeDateUTC "08-20-2019 02:01:09" -MaxExecPurge 200&nbsp;</div></li><li><span style="background-color: transparent;"><span style="background-color: transparent;">Use “OOCentralURL”, “UserName” and “Passwd” parameters to connect to the OO Central Application. The “OOCentralURL”, “UserName” and “Passwd” parameters are mandatory.<br></span></span></li><li><div>Use “BeforeDateUTC” parameter to purge debugger flow events data prior to certain date and time in UTC. The “BeforeDateUTC” parameter value must be in the following format: “MM-DD-YYYY HH24:MI:SS”. The “BeforeDateUTC” parameter is optional. If no value is specified, script uses current date and time as the default value for this parameter.<br></div></li><li><div>Use “MaxExecPurge” parameter to restrict amount of debugger flow events data that would be purged. The “MaxExecPurge” parameter is optional. If no value is specified, script uses default value of 100 for “MaxExecPurge” parameter.<br></div></li></ol></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></span></div></span></div>